On leaving the castle and descending the hill our visitor would see on his right the little church ol' S. Peter, and on his left, in the angle between the road along which he was walking, and a track which led eastwards to Chesterton, the somewhat larger church os S. Giles. This is the church built by Pycot and his wile in 1092, adjoining which was the first house for their Canons (pp. 39, 46) in which they resided until Pain Peverel gave thern “thirteen acres in the fields os Cambridge round the springs oi Bamwell'' (p. 43). The ground between this church and the river was claimed by the Prior in 1286 as the gift os Countess Matilda to his convent (p. 168)

From this point where iour ways meet-the Carlax oi Cambridge-a very short space oi street leads down to the river at the point where the Great Bridge now stands. ln the thirteenth century the ancient iord had been replaced by a bridge, of course oi wood; and in 1279 the commissioners of Edward l found that it was “so broken and dislocated that the carriages oi noble persons and others sall into the water in such a way that both men and horses come to the surlace with difficulty¹.''
